Use ASP.NET Core's **`WebApplicationFactory<T>`** — it hosts your app in-memory and gives you an `HttpClient` that talks to it without opening a real port. Then wire that client into the MCP C# SDK's transport.

### Setup

```bash
dotnet add package Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing
dotnet add package ModelContextProtocol  # MCP C# SDK
```

### Example test

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing;
using ModelContextProtocol.Client;
using ModelContextProtocol.Protocol.Transport;

public class McpIntegrationTests : IClassFixture<WebApplicationFactory<Program>>
{
    private readonly WebApplicationFactory<Program> _factory;

    public McpIntegrationTests(WebApplicationFactory<Program> factory)
    {
        _factory = factory;
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task ListTools_ReturnsExpectedTools()
    {
        // WebApplicationFactory gives you an HttpClient backed by
        // an in-memory test server — no real port, no real network.
        var httpClient = _factory.CreateClient();

        // Use the SDK's Streamable HTTP transport, injecting the test client
        var transport = new SseClientTransport(
            new SseClientTransportOptions
            {
                Endpoint = new Uri(httpClient.BaseAddress!, "/mcp"),
                // Name shown during initialize handshake
                Name = "integration-test"
            },
            httpClient   // ← the in-memory client
        );

        await using var mcpClient = await McpClientFactory.CreateAsync(transport);

        var tools = await mcpClient.ListToolsAsync();

        Assert.NotEmpty(tools);
        Assert.Contains(tools, t => t.Name == "my_tool");
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task CallTool_ReturnsCorrectResult()
    {
        var httpClient = _factory.CreateClient();
        var transport = new SseClientTransport(
            new SseClientTransportOptions
            {
                Endpoint = new Uri(httpClient.BaseAddress!, "/mcp"),
                Name = "integration-test"
            },
            httpClient
        );

        await using var mcpClient = await McpClientFactory.CreateAsync(transport);

        var result = await mcpClient.CallToolAsync(
            "my_tool",
            new Dictionary<string, object?> { ["input"] = "hello" });

        Assert.False(result.IsError);
        Assert.Contains("expected output", result.Content[0].Text);
    }
}
```

### Key points

| Concept | Detail |
|---|---|
| **No real server** | `WebApplicationFactory` hosts your `Program` in-process with a test `HttpClient` |
| **Full protocol fidelity** | The MCP SDK's transport performs the real `initialize` → `initialized` handshake, SSE streaming, and JSON-RPC framing |
| **`Program` visibility** | Add `<InternalsVisibleTo Include="YourTestProject" />` to your server's `.csproj`, or use a `public partial class Program { }` marker |
| **Customization** | Override `WithWebHostBuilder` to swap services (e.g., mock a database) before each test |

This gives you real end-to-end MCP coverage (serialization, routing, middleware, tool dispatch) with the speed of an in-process call.
